<div><div><h2>-</h2></div><div>members of the european parliament <a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/headlines/economy/20171110sto87807/paradise-papers-debate-eu-countries-should-crack-down-on-tax-dodging">discussing the paradise papers revelations </a>this week said that the european union member states should take steps to clamp down on tax avoidance schemes. the statement published on the parliament\xe2\x80\x99s website came in the aftermath of the latest icij investigation which exposed the systemic use of companies in offshore jurisdictions by wealthy individuals and corporations. european commissioner for economic and financial affairs pierre moscovici likened professionals that facilitate tax evasion to \xe2\x80\x9cvampires.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cthey don\xe2\x80\x99t seem to fear anything except light so it is up to us to generate that light\xe2\x80\x9d moscovici said at the meeting in strasbourg \xc2\xa0<a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-tax-paradisepapers/eus-moscovici-urges-fast-action-against-tax-vampires-after-paradise-papers-iduskbn1de0un">according to reuters</a>. the <a href="/paradisepapers">paradise papers findings</a> add to the revelations from icij\xe2\x80\x99s 2016 <a href="/panamapapers">panama papers investigation</a> which led the european to set up a special pana committee to probe abusive business practices involving the offshore financial industry. the pana committee is expected to vote on its final report in december and one of the conclusions is that \xe2\x80\x9csome eu countries have failed to tackle money laundering and tax evasion\xe2\x80\x9d according to the parliament\xe2\x80\x99s website. european finance ministers have also recently announced that by the end of the year they will release a \xe2\x80\x9cblacklist\xe2\x80\x9d of jurisdictions that are said to facilitate tax avoidance and tax evasion. \xe2\x80\x9cthe extensive use of loopholes in tax systems and the intentional or unintentional creation of special tax regimes are harming our economy harming competition increasing inequality\xe2\x80\x9d said czech member lud\xc4\x9bk niedermayer. united nations human rights experts also <a href="http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp newsid=58072#.wgyqfhopj27">voiced concerns on aggressive tax avoidance</a> after icij media partners in more than 60 countries published the paradise papers last week. <a href="http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp newsid=58072#.wgyqfhopj27">the experts urged un member states</a> to \xe2\x80\x9cstop harmful tax competition\xe2\x80\x9d and said law firms that facilitate tax avoidance schemes should \xe2\x80\x9cassume their responsibility.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cwealthy individuals and international corporations are continuing to engage in unethical practices reducing their tax burdens to minimal levels by using tax havens which undermines the realisation of human rights\xe2\x80\x9d said juan pablo <a href="http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp newsid=58072#.wgyqfhopj27">bohoslavsky</a> a un independent expert. <em>the european parliament will host a public hearing on the paradise papers in brussels on november 28 which will include presentations from icij&#8217;s partners. more <a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/committees/en/pana/events-hearings.html id=20171109che02761">details are available on the pana committee&#8217;s website</a>.</em></div></div>